an ROTCE of 20%.&#8221;</font></div><div><font><br></font></div><div><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:12.40pt">Dimon continued&#58; </font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:400;line-height:12.40pt">&#8220;Each line of business performed well. In the CIB, IB fees rose 16% as ECM and M&#38;A activity picked up against a supportive backdrop. We continued to benefit from higher client activity and demand for financing in Markets, with record third-quarter Markets revenue of nearly $9 billion. In CCB, we ranked #1 in U.S. retail deposits for the fifth consecutive year, and we continue to acquire new accounts at a robust pace, adding more than 400,000 net new checking accounts this quarter. Additionally, in wealth management, first-time investors surpassed 43,000, setting a new record. Finally, in AWM, revenue topped $6 billion, and AUM net inflows remained strong at $109 billion, highlighting the strength of the franchise.&#8221; </font></div><div><font><br></font></div><div><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:12.40pt">Dimon added&#58; </font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:400;line-height:12.40pt">&#8220;While there have been some signs of a softening, particularly in job growth, the U.S. economy generally remained resilient. However, there continues to be a heightened degree of uncertainty stemming from complex geopolitical conditions, tariffs and trade uncertainty, elevated asset prices and the risk of sticky inflation. As always, we hope for the best, but these complex forces reinforce why we prepare the Firm for a wide range of scenarios.&#8221;</font></div><div><font><br></font></div><div><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:12.40pt">Dimon concluded&#58; </font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:400;line-height:12.40pt">&#8220;I want to thank our exceptional employees across the globe. style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%"> </font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt;margin-top:3pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:700;line-height:120%">Discussion of Results&#58;</font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Net income was $14.4 billion, up 12%.</font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Net revenue was $47.1 billion, up 9%. Net interest income was $24.1 billion, up 2%. Noninterest revenue was $23.0 billion, up 16%. </font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Net interest income excluding Markets</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:6.5pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;position:relative;top:-3.5pt;vertical-align:baseline">2</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%"> was $23.4 billion, flat to the prior year, driven by the impact of lower rates and deposit margin compression, predominantly offset by higher revolving balances in Card Services and higher wholesale deposit balances. Noninterest revenue excluding Markets</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:6.5pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;position:relative;top:-3.5pt;vertical-align:baseline">2</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%"> was $14.8 billion, up 16%, largely driven by higher asset management fees in AWM and CCB, higher investment banking fees, higher auto operating lease income and higher Payments fees. Markets revenue was $8.9 billion, up 25%.</font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Noninterest expense was $24.3 billion, up 8%, predominantly driven by higher compensation, including higher revenue-related compensation and growth in front office employees, as well as higher brokerage expense and distribution fees, higher auto lease depreciation and higher marketing expense, partially offset by lower legal expense.</font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">The provision for credit losses was $3.4 billion. Net charge-offs were $2.6 billion, up $506 million, predominantly driven by Wholesale and Card Services. The net reserve build was $810 million and included $608 million in Consumer and $205 million in Wholesale. In the prior year, the provision was $3.1 billion, net charge-offs were $2.1 billion and the net reserve build was $1.0 billion. </font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font><br></font></div><div style="height:42.75pt;position:relative;width:100%"><div style="bottom:0;position:absolute;width:100%"><div style="text-align:center"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">2 </font></div></div></div><div style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%"> </font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt;margin-top:3pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:700;line-height:120%">Discussion of Results&#58;</font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Net income was $5.0 billion, up 24%. </font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Net revenue</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:6.5pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;position:relative;top:-3.5pt;vertical-align:baseline">13</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%"> was $19.5 billion, up 9%. Banking &#38; Wealth Management net revenue was $11.0 billion, up 9%, predominantly driven by higher net interest income on higher deposit margin, reflecting the impact of changes in funds transfer pricing</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:6.5pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;position:relative;top:-3.5pt;vertical-align:baseline">13</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">, as well as higher asset management fees in J.P. Morgan Wealth Management. Home Lending net revenue was $1.3 billion, down 3%, largely driven by lower net interest income. Card Services &#38; Auto net revenue was $7.2 billion, up 12%, driven by higher Card Services net interest income on higher revolving balances, as well as higher auto operating lease income, partially offset by lower card income on lower net interchange and higher new account origination costs.</font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Noninterest expense was $10.3 billion, up 7%, predominantly driven by higher auto lease depreciation, higher marketing expense and higher compensation for bankers and advisors.</font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">The provision for credit losses was $2.5 billion. Net charge-offs were $2.0 billion, up $44 million, primarily driven by Card Services. The net reserve build was $575 million, reflecting $550 million in Card Services and $100 million in Home Lending. The build was driven by loan growth in Card Services and updates to certain macroeconomic variables in Card Services and Home Lending, partially offset by reduced borrower uncertainty. In the prior year, the provision was $2.8 billion, net charge-offs were $1.9 billion and the net reserve build was $876 million.</font></div><div><font><br></font></div><div><font><br></font></div><div style="height:45pt;position:relative;width:100%"><div style="bottom:0;position:absolute;width:100%"><div style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:100%">%</font></td><td colspan="3" style="background-color:#ffffff;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #828282;border-top:0.5pt solid #828282;padding:0 1pt"></td><td style="background-color:#ffffff;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #828282;border-top:0.5pt solid #828282;padding:2px 0 2px 1pt;text-align:left;vertical-align:bottom"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:100%">$</font></td><td style="background-color:#ffffff;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #828282;border-top:0.5pt solid #828282;padding:2px 0;text-align:right;vertical-align:bottom"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:100%">1,210&#160;</font></td><td style="background-color:#ffffff;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #828282;border-top:0.5pt solid #828282;padding:2px 1pt 2px 0;text-align:right;vertical-align:bottom"></td><td colspan="2" style="background-color:#ffffff;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #828282;border-top:0.5pt solid #828282;padding:2px 0 2px 1pt;text-align:right;vertical-align:bottom"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:100%">21&#160;</font></td><td style="background-color:#ffffff;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #828282;border-top:0.5pt solid #828282;padding:2px 1pt 2px 0;text-align:right;vertical-align:bottom"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:100%">%</font></td></tr></table></div><div style="text-align:center"><font><br></font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="background-color:#ffffff;color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:700;line-height:120%">Discussion of Results&#58;</font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="background-color:#ffffff;color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Net income was $6.9 billion, up 21%. </font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Net revenue was $19.9 billion, up 17%. Banking &#38; Payments revenue was $9.5 billion, up 10%. Investment Banking revenue was $2.7 billion, up 14%. Investment Banking fees were $2.6 billion, up 16%, driven by higher fees across all products. Payments revenue was $4.9 billion, up 13%. Excluding the net impact of equity investments, which included higher markdowns in the prior year, Payments revenue was up 6%, driven by higher deposit balances and fee growth, partially offset by deposit margin compression. Lending revenue was $1.9 billion, down 1%.</font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Markets &#38; Securities Services revenue was $10.4 billion, up 24%. Markets revenue was $8.9 billion, up 25%. Fixed Income Markets revenue was $5.6 billion, up 21%, largely driven by higher revenue in Rates, Credit and the Securitized Products Group</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:6.5pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;position:relative;top:-3.5pt;vertical-align:baseline">14</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">. Equity Markets revenue was $3.3 billion, up 33%, predominantly driven by higher revenue across products, particularly in Prime. Securities Services revenue was $1.4 billion, up 7%, driven by higher deposit balances as well as fee growth on higher client activity and market levels, partially offset by deposit margin compression.</font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Noninterest expense was $9.7 billion, up 11%, largely driven by higher compensation and brokerage expense.</font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">The provision for credit losses was $809 million, driven by net lending activity, the impact of charge-offs related to what appears to be borrower-related collateral irregularities in certain secured lending facilities and changes in credit quality of certain exposures, partially offset by updates to macroeconomic variables. Net charge-offs were $567 million, and the net reserve build was $242 million. In the prior year, the provision was $316 million, the net reserve build was $160 million and net charge-offs were $156 million. </font></div><div id="i40cf4d1331294cbd96d7444dec59e431_13"></div><div style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:700;line-height:120%">Discussion of Results&#58;</font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Net income was $1.7 billion, up 23%. </font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Net revenue was $6.1 billion, up 12%, predominantly driven by growth in management fees due to strong net inflows and higher average market levels, as well as higher brokerage activity.</font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Noninterest expense was $3.8 billion, up 5%, driven by higher compensation, primarily higher revenue-related compensation and continued&#160;growth in private banking advisor teams, as well as higher distribution fees, largely offset by lower legal expense. </font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">The provision for credit losses was $59 million, driven by the impact of a charge-off related to a single client. Net charge-offs were $62 million, and the net reserve release was $3 million. In the prior year, the provision was $4 million.</font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Assets under management were $4.6 trillion, up 18%, and client assets were $6.8 trillion, up 20%. These increases were each driven by continued net inflows and higher market levels.</font></div><div style="height:45pt;position:relative;width:100%"><div style="bottom:0;position:absolute;width:100%"><div style="text-align:center"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">4 style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:700;line-height:120%">Discussion of Results&#58;  </font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Net income was $825 million, down $1.0 billion.</font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Net revenue was $1.7 billion, down $1.4 billion. Net interest income was $1.4 billion, down $1.5 billion, predominantly driven by the impact of lower rates and changes in funds transfer pricing</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:6.5pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;position:relative;top:-3.5pt;vertical-align:baseline">13</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%"> for consumer deposits. Noninterest revenue was $297 million, up $142 million. </font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Noninterest expense was $445 million, down $144 million.</font></div><div><font><br></font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font><br></font></div><div style="height:45pt;position:relative;width:100%"><div style="bottom:0;position:absolute;width:100%"><div style="text-align:center"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">5 </font></div></div></div><div id="i40cf4d1331294cbd96d7444dec59e431_19"></div><hr style="page-break-after:always"><div style="min-height:45pt;width:100%"><div><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">JPMorgan&#160;Chase &#38; Co.</font></div><div><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">News Release</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'JPMC Tiempos',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%"> </font></div></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:700;line-height:120%">2.    Notes on non-GAAP financial measures&#58;</font></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font><br></font></div><div style="padding-left:18pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-18pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">a.</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:11.07pt">The Firm prepares its Consolidated Financial Statements in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the U.S. (&#8220;U.S. GAAP&#8221;). That presentation, which is referred to as &#8220;reported&#8221; basis, provides the reader with an understanding of the Firm&#8217;s results that can be tracked consistently from year-to-year and enables a comparison of the Firm&#8217;s performance with the U.S. GAAP financial statements of other companies. In addition to analyzing the Firm&#8217;s results on a reported basis, management reviews Firmwide results, including the overhead ratio, on a &#8220;managed&#8221; basis&#59; these Firmwide managed basis results are non-GAAP financial measures. The Firm also reviews the results of the lines of business on a managed basis. The Firm&#8217;s definition of managed basis starts, in each case, with the reported U.S. GAAP results and includes certain reclassifications to present total net revenue for the Firm as a whole and for each of the reportable business segments and Corporate on a fully taxable-equivalent basis. Accordingly, revenue from investments that receive tax credits and tax-exempt securities is presented in the managed results on a basis comparable to taxable investments and securities. These financial measures allow management to assess the comparability of revenue from year-to-year arising from both taxable and tax-exempt sources. The corresponding income tax impact related to tax-exempt items is recorded within income tax expense. These adjustments have no impact on net income as reported by the Firm as a whole or by each of the lines of business and Corporate. For a reconciliation of the Firm&#8217;s results from a reported to managed basis, refer to page 7 of the Earnings Release Financial Supplement.</font></div><div style="padding-left:18pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-18pt"><font><br></font></div><div style="padding-left:18pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-18pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">b.</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:10.5pt">Tangible common equity (&#8220;TCE&#8221;), return on tangible common equity (&#8220;ROTCE&#8221;) and tangible book value per share (&#8220;TBVPS&#8221;) are each non-GAAP financial measures. TCE represents the Firm&#8217;s common stockholders&#8217; equity (i.e., total stockholders&#8217; equity less preferred stock) less goodwill and identifiable intangible assets (other than mortgage servicing rights), net of related deferred tax liabilities. For a reconciliation from common stockholders&#8217; equity to TCE, refer to page 10 of the Earnings Release Financial Supplement. ROTCE measures the Firm&#8217;s net income applicable to common equity as a percentage of average TCE. TBVPS represents the Firm&#8217;s TCE at period-end divided by common shares at period-end. Book value per share was $124.96, $122.51 and $115.15 at September 30, 2025, June 30, 2025 and September 30, 2024, respectively. TCE, ROTCE and TBVPS are utilized by the Firm, as well as investors and analysts, in assessing the Firm&#8217;s use of equity.</font></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font><br></font></div><div style="padding-left:18pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-18pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">c.</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:11.07pt">In addition to reviewing net interest income (&#8220;NII&#8221;) and noninterest revenue (&#8220;NIR&#8221;) on a managed basis, management also reviews these metrics excluding Markets, which is composed of Fixed Income Markets and Equity Markets. Markets revenue consists of principal transactions, fees, commissions and other income, as well as net interest income. These metrics, which exclude Markets, are non-GAAP financial measures. Management reviews these metrics to assess the performance of the Firm&#8217;s lending, investing (including asset-liability management) and deposit-raising activities, apart from any volatility associated with Markets activities. In addition, management also assesses Markets business performance on a total revenue basis as offsets may occur across revenue lines. For example, securities that generate net interest income may be risk-managed by derivatives that are reflected at fair value in principal transactions revenue. Management believes these measures provide investors and analysts with alternative measures to analyze the revenue trends of the Firm. For a reconciliation of NII and NIR from reported to excluding Markets, refer to page 28 of the Earnings Release Financial Supplement. For additional information on Markets revenue, refer to pages 81-82 of the Firm&#8217;s 2024 Form 10-K.</font></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font><br></font></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font><br></font></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font><br></font></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font><br></font></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font><br></font></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font><br></font></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font><br></font></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font><br></font></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font><br></font></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font><br></font></div><div style="height:45pt;position:relative;width:100%"><div style="bottom:0;position:absolute;width:100%"><div style="text-align:center"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">6 </font></div></div></div><div id="i40cf4d1331294cbd96d7444dec59e431_22"></div><hr style="page-break-after:always"><div style="min-height:45pt;width:100%"><div><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">JPMorgan&#160;Chase &#38; Co.</font></div><div><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">News Release</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'JPMC Tiempos',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%"> </font></div></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons Semibold',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:700;line-height:120%"> </font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:700;line-height:120%">Additional notes&#58;</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt;padding-left:18pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-18pt"><font><br></font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt;padding-left:18pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-18pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%">3.</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%;padding-left:10.5pt">Estimated. Refer to&#160;Note 21 of the Firm's Quarterly Report on Form 10-Q for the quarterly period ended June 30, 2025 and Note 27 of the Firm&#8217;s 2024 Form 10-K for additional information.</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt;padding-left:18pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-18pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%">4.</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%;padding-left:10.5pt">Estimated. Cash and marketable securities include end-of-period eligible high-quality liquid assets (&#8220;HQLA&#8221;), excluding regulatory prescribed haircuts under the liquidity coverage ratio (&#8220;LCR&#8221;) rule where applicable, for both the Firm and the excess HQLA-eligible securities included as part of the excess liquidity at JPMorgan Chase Bank, N.A., which are not transferable to non-bank affiliates and thus excluded from the Firm&#8217;s LCR. Also include other end-of-period unencumbered marketable securities, such as equity and debt securities. Does not include borrowing capacity at Federal Home Loan Banks and the discount window at the Federal Reserve Bank. Refer to Liquidity Risk Management on pages 50-57 of the Firm's Quarterly Report on Form 10-Q for the quarterly period ended June 30, 2025 and pages 108-115 of the Firm&#8217;s 2024 Form 10-K for additional information.</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt;padding-left:18pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-18pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Co.</font></div><div><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">News Release</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'JPMC Tiempos',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%"> </font></div></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font><br></font></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">JPMorgan Chase &#38; Co. (NYSE&#58; JPM) is a leading financial services firm based in the United States of America (&#8220;U.S.&#8221;), with operations worldwide. JPMorganChase had</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:12pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%"> </font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">$4.6 trillion in assets and $360&#160;billion in stockholders&#8217; equity as of September 30, 2025. The Firm is a leader in investment banking, financial services for consumers and small businesses, commercial banking, financial transaction processing and asset management. Under the J.P. Morgan and Chase brands, the Firm serves millions of customers predominantly in the U.S., and many of the world&#8217;s most prominent corporate, institutional and government clients globally. Information about JPMorgan Chase &#38; Co. is available at </font><font style="color:#4f81bd;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">www.jpmorganchase.com</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">.</font></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font><br></font></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">JPMorgan Chase &#38; Co. will host a conference call today, October 14, 2025, at 8&#58;30 a.m. (ET) to present third-quarter 2025 financial results. The replay will be available via webcast on </font><font style="color:#4f81bd;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">www.jpmorganchase.com</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%"> under Investor Relations, Events &#38; Presentations. Additional detailed financial, statistical and business-related information is included in a financial supplement. The earnings release and the financial supplement are available at </font><font style="color:#4f81bd;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">www.jpmorganchase.com</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">.</font></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font><br></font></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">This earnings release contains forward-looking statements within the meaning of the Private Securities Litigation Reform Act of 1995. These statements are based on the current beliefs and expectations of JPMorgan Chase &#38; Co.&#8217;s management and are subject to significant risks and uncertainties. Actual results may differ from those set forth in the forward-looking statements. Factors that could cause JPMorgan Chase &#38; Co.&#8217;s actual results to differ materially from those described in the forward-looking statements can be found in JPMorgan Chase &#38; Co.&#8217;s Annual Report on Form 10-K for the year ended December 31, 2024 and Quarterly Report on Form 10-Q for the quarterly period ended June 30, 2025, which have been filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission and are available on JPMorgan Chase &#38; Co.&#8217;s website (</font><font style="color:#006ebf;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">https&#58;&#47;&#47;jpmorganchaseco.gcs-web.com&#47;ir&#47;sec-other-filings&#47;overview</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">), and on the Securities and Exchange Commission&#8217;s website (</font><font style="color:#006ebf;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">www.sec.gov</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">). As of December 31, 2024 and September 30, 2024, CET1 capital reflected the remaining $720 million CECL benefit. Refer to&#160;Note 21 of the Firm&#8217;s Quarterly Report on Form 10-Q for the quarterly period ended June 30, 2025, and Note 27 of the Firm&#8217;s 2024 Form 10-K for additional information.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(e)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Reflects the Firm&#8217;s ratios under the Basel III Standardized approach. Refer to page 9 for further information on the Firm&#8217;s capital metrics.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(f)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:3.36pt">Estimated.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(g)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Included an FDIC special assessment accrual release of $323 million for the three months ended March 31, 2025, and an accrual increase of $725 million for the three months ended March 31, 2024. Refer to&#160;Note 6 on page 228 of the Firm&#8217;s 2024 Form 10-K for additional information.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(h)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Included a $7.9 billion net gain related to Visa shares recorded in the second quarter of 2024. style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%"> </font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(a)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Effective April 1, 2025, the Firm refined the historical proxy time series inputs to one of its VaR models to more appropriately reflect the risk exposure from certain securitization warehousing loan positions. With this refined time series, the average Total VaR for the three months ended March 31, 2025, December 31, 2024 and September 30, 2024 would have been lower by $(5) million, $(5) million and $(4) million, respectively. Refer to Commercial &#38; Investment Bank VaR on page 19 for further information.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(b)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Earnings-at-risk estimates the Firm&#8217;s interest rate exposure for a given interest rate scenario. It is presented as a sensitivity to a baseline, which includes net interest income and certain interest rate sensitive fees. The baseline reflects certain assumptions relating to the Federal Reserve&#8217;s balance sheet policy (e.g., quantitative tightening and usage at the Reverse Repurchase Facility) that require management judgment. The Firm&#8217;s actual net interest income for the rate shifts presented may differ as the earnings-at-risk scenarios are modelled as instantaneous shifts and exclude any actions that could be taken by the Firm or its clients and customers in response to instantaneous rate changes. Other significant assumptions in the earnings-at-risk scenarios may also differ from actual results, including mortgage prepayments and deposits rates paid. Refer to pages 147-148 of the Firm&#8217;s Annual Report on Form 10-K for the year ended December 31, 2024 for additional information.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(c)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:2.02pt">Reflects the simultaneous shift of U.S. dollar and non-U.S. dollar rates. At September 30, 2024 represents the total of the Firm&#8217;s U.S. dollar and non-U.S. dollar sensitivities as presented in Structural interest rate risk management of the Firm&#8217;s Quarterly Report on Form 10-Q for the quarterly period ended September 30, 2024.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(d)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Refer to Reconciliation from Reported to Managed Basis on page 7 for a further discussion of managed basis.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(e)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Estimated.</font></div><div style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(a) Includes brokerage-related held-for-investment customer receivables, which are classified in accrued interest and accounts receivable, and all other interest-earning assets, which are classified in other assets, on the Consolidated Balance Sheets.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(b)&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All other interest-bearing liabilities include brokerage-related customer payables.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font Taxable-equivalent amounts are used where applicable. Refer to&#160;Note 5 of the Firm&#8217;s 2024 Form 10-K for additional information on hedge accounting.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:115%">(d) The rates reflect the impact of interest earned on cash collateral where the cash collateral has been netted against certain derivative payables.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(e)&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Net yield on interest-earning assets excluding Markets is a non-GAAP financial measure. style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">The Firm prepares its Consolidated Financial Statements using accounting principles generally accepted in the U.S. (&#8220;U.S. GAAP&#8221;). That presentation, which is referred to as &#8220;reported&#8221; basis, provides the reader with an understanding of the Firm&#8217;s results that can be tracked consistently from year-to-year and enables a comparison of the Firm&#8217;s performance with other companies&#8217; U.S. GAAP financial statements. In addition to analyzing the Firm&#8217;s results on a reported basis, management reviews Firmwide results, including the overhead ratio, on a &#8220;managed&#8221; basis&#59; these Firmwide managed basis results are non-GAAP financial measures. The Firm also reviews the results of the lines of business on a managed basis. Refer to the notes on Non-GAAP Financial Measures on page 28 for additional information on managed basis.</font></div><div><font><br></font></div><div><font 1pt"></td><td colspan="3" style="display:none"></td></tr></table></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(a)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Excludes mortgage loans past due and insured by U.S. government agencies, which are primarily 90 or more days past due. These loans have been excluded based upon the government guarantee. At September 30, 2025, June 30, 2025, March 31, 2025, December 31, 2024 and September 30, 2024, mortgage loans 90 or more days past due and insured by U.S. government agencies were $65 million, $68 million, $81 million, $84 million and $88 million, respectively. In addition, the Firm&#8217;s policy is generally to exempt credit card loans from being placed on nonaccrual status as permitted by regulatory guidance.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(b)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">At September 30, 2025, June 30, 2025, March 31, 2025, December 31, 2024 and September 30, 2024, excluded mortgage loans 30 or more days past due and insured by U.S. government agencies of $95 million, $99 million, $114 million, $122 million and $126 million, respectively. These amounts have been excluded based upon the government guarantee.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(c)</font><font in the Firm&#8217;s 2024 Form 10-K.</font></div><div style="text-indent:9pt"><font><br></font></div><div style="text-indent:9pt"><font><br></font></div><div Prior-period amounts have been revised to conform with the current presentation.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(c)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:2.02pt">Consists primarily of centrally managed credit valuation adjustments (&#8220;CVA&#8221;), funding valuation adjustments (&#8220;FVA&#8221;) on derivatives, other valuation adjustments, and certain components of fair value option elected liabilities, which are primarily reported in principal transactions revenue. Corporate Banking &#38; Global Investment Banking reflecting the subsequent alignment of certain business activities after the Firm&#8217;s Business Segment reorganization in the second quarter of 2024. Prior-period amounts have been revised to conform with the current presentation.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%">(d)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%;padding-left:1.69pt">In the second quarter of 2025, the Middle Market Banking client coverage segment was renamed Commercial &#38; Specialized Industries.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%">(e)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%;padding-left:1.69pt">On January 1, 2025, $5.6 billion of loans were realigned from Global Corporate Banking to Fixed Income Markets.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%">(f)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%;padding-left:3.36pt">In the first quarter of 2025, 219 employees were transferred to Corporate as a result of the centralization of certain functions.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%">(g)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%;padding-left:1.69pt">Prior-period amounts have been revised to conform with the presentation in the Firm&#8217;s Quarterly Report on Form 10-Q for the quarterly period ended September 30, 2024.</font></div><div style="text-indent:9pt"><font><br></font></div><div><font><br></font></div><div style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(a)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Client deposits and other third-party liabilities pertain to the Payments and Securities Services businesses.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(b)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Effective April 1, 2025, the Firm refined the historical proxy time series inputs to one of its VaR models to more appropriately reflect the risk exposure from certain securitization warehousing loan positions. With this refined time series, the average VaR for each of the following reported components would have been lower by the following amounts&#58; CIB trading VaR by fixed income risk type of $(7) million, $(6) million and $(6) million, CIB trading VaR of $(6) million, $(5) million and $(4) million, and CIB VaR of $(5) million, $(6) million and $(5) million for the three months ended March 31, 2025, December 31, 2024 and September 30, 2024, respectively.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(c)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:2.02pt">CIB trading VaR includes substantially all market-making and client-driven activities, as well as certain risk management activities in CIB, including credit spread sensitivity to CVA. Refer to VaR measurement on pages 143&#8211;145 of the Firm&#8217;s 2024 Form 10-K and pages 77&#8211;80 of the Firm&#8217;s Quarterly Report on Form 10-Q for the quarterly period ended June 30, 2025 for further information.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(d)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Diversification benefit represents the difference between the portfolio VaR and the sum of its individual components. This reflects the non-additive nature of VaR due to imperfect correlation across CIB risks.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(e)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Credit Portfolio VaR includes the derivative CVA, hedges of the CVA and credit protection purchased against certain retained loans and lending-related commitments, which are reported in principal transactions revenue. This VaR does not include the retained loan portfolio, which is not reported at fair value.</font></div><div style="height:18pt;position:relative;width:100%"><div September 30, 2024, the allowance for credit losses on investment securities was $72 million, $75 million, $85 million, $105&#160;million and $123&#160;million, respectively.</font></div><div Firm&#8217;s 2024 Form 10-K.</font></div><div style="text-indent:9pt"><font><br></font></div><div><font><br></font></div><div><font><br></font></div><div style="padding:2px 1pt;text-align:left;vertical-align:bottom"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:700;line-height:100%">JPMORGAN CHASE &#38; CO.</font></td><td colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td><td colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td><td colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td><td colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td><td style="height:23px;margin-bottom:5pt;vertical-align:text-bottom;width:163px"></div></td></tr><tr style="height:9pt"><td colspan="9" style="padding:2px 1pt;text-align:left;vertical-align:bottom"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8pt;font-weight:700;line-height:100%">NON-GAAP FINANCIAL MEASURES</font></td><td colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td><td colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td><td colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td></tr><tr style="height:9pt"><td colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td><td colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td><td colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td><td colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td><td colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td><td colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td></tr></table></div><div style="margin-bottom:2pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:700;line-height:120%">Non-GAAP Financial Measures</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:2pt;padding-left:18pt;text-indent:-18pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(a)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:7.25pt">In addition to analyzing the Firm&#8217;s results on a reported basis, management reviews Firmwide results, including the overhead ratio, on a </font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:700;line-height:120%">&#8220;managed&#8221; basis</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">&#59; these Firmwide managed basis results are non-GAAP financial measures. The Firm also reviews the results of the lines of business on a managed basis. The Firm&#8217;s definition of managed basis starts, in each case, with the reported U.S. GAAP results and includes certain reclassifications to present total net revenue for the Firm as a whole and for each of the reportable business segments and Corporate on an FTE basis. Accordingly, revenue from investments that receive tax credits and tax-exempt securities is presented in the managed results on a basis comparable to taxable investments and securities. These financial measures allow management to assess the comparability of revenue from year-to-year arising from both taxable and tax-exempt sources. The corresponding income tax impact related to tax-exempt items is recorded within income tax expense. These adjustments have no impact on net income as reported by the Firm as a whole or by each of the lines of business and Corporate.</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:2pt;padding-left:18pt;text-indent:-18pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(b)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:700;line-height:120%;padding-left:7.25pt">Pre-provision profit </font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">is a non-GAAP financial measure which represents total net revenue less total noninterest expense. The Firm believes that this financial measure is useful in assessing the ability of a lending institution to generate income in excess of its provision for credit losses.</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:2pt;padding-left:18pt;text-indent:-18pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(c)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:700;line-height:120%;padding-left:7.74pt">TCE, ROTCE, and TBVPS</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%"> are each non-GAAP financial measures. TCE represents the Firm&#8217;s common stockholders&#8217; equity (i.e., total stockholders&#8217; equity less preferred stock) less goodwill and identifiable intangible assets (other than MSRs), net of related deferred tax liabilities. ROTCE measures the Firm&#8217;s net income applicable to common equity as a percentage of average TCE. TBVPS represents the Firm&#8217;s TCE at period-end divided by common shares at period-end. TCE, ROTCE, and TBVPS are utilized by the Firm, as well as investors and analysts, in assessing the Firm&#8217;s use of equity.</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:2pt;padding-left:18pt;text-indent:-18pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(d)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:7.25pt">In addition to reviewing net interest income (&#8220;NII&#8221;), net yield, and noninterest revenue (&#8220;NIR&#8221;) on a managed basis, management also reviews these metrics </font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:700;line-height:120%">excluding Markets</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">, which is composed of Fixed Income Markets and Equity Markets, as shown below. Markets revenue consists of principal transactions, fees, commissions and other income, as well as net interest income.These metrics, which exclude</font><font style="color:#ee2724;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%"> </font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Markets, are non-GAAP financial measures. Management reviews these metrics to assess the performance of the Firm&#8217;s lending, investing (including asset-liability management) and deposit-raising activities, apart from any volatility associated with Markets activities. In addition, management also assesses Markets business performance on a total revenue basis as offsets may occur across revenue lines. For example, securities that generate net interest income may be risk-managed by derivatives that are reflected at fair value in principal transactions revenue. Management believes these measures provide investors and analysts with alternative measures to analyze the revenue trends of the Firm. For additional information on Markets revenue, refer to pages 81-82 of the Firm&#8217;s 2024 Form 10-K.</font></div><div style="padding-left:18pt"><table if(e)e.style.display='block';Show.LastAR=e};Show.hideAR=function(){Show.LastAR.style.display='none'};Show.toggleNext=function(a){var e=a;while(e.nodeName!='DIV')e=e.nextSibling;if(!e.style){}else if(!e.style.display){}else{var d,p_;if(e.style.display=='none'){d='block';p='-'}else{d='none';p='+'}
